		<item>
		<title>
		By: CS		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.vercel.app/threshold-theory#comment-11877</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[CS]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 12 Oct 2014 10:30:22 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6220#comment-11877</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[The Terman study and the literature on extreme ability are misunderstood in this article. Looking at rates of invention, discovery, and success higher IQ continues to give strong gains as high as you go. But in a roughly Gaussian distribution the number of people at a given level falls off super-exponentially. I.e. the more able you are, the better your chances, but the number of people at high ability levels falls off a lot faster than their per person chances improve, so most successful people are not at the extremes.

http://infoproc.blogspot.com/2014/07/success-ability-and-all-that.html

As Hsu says:

&quot;In the SMPY study probability of having published a literary work or earned a patent was increasing with ability even within the top 1%. The &quot;IQ over 120 doesn&#039;t matter&quot; meme falls apart if one measures individual likelihood of success, as opposed to the total number of individuals at, e.g., IQ 120 vs IQ 145 who have achieved some milestone. The base population of the former is 100 times that of the latter!&quot;]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>The Terman study and the literature on extreme ability are misunderstood in this article. Looking at rates of invention, discovery, and success higher IQ continues to give strong gains as high as you go. But in a roughly Gaussian distribution the number of people at a given level falls off super-exponentially. I.e. the more able you are, the better your chances, but the number of people at high ability levels falls off a lot faster than their per person chances improve, so most successful people are not at the extremes.</p>
<p><a href="http://infoproc.blogspot.com/2014/07/success-ability-and-all-that.html" rel="nofollow ugc">http://infoproc.blogspot.com/2014/07/success-ability-and-all-that.html</a></p>
<p>As Hsu says:</p>
<p>&#8220;In the SMPY study probability of having published a literary work or earned a patent was increasing with ability even within the top 1%. The &#8220;IQ over 120 doesn&#8217;t matter&#8221; meme falls apart if one measures individual likelihood of success, as opposed to the total number of individuals at, e.g., IQ 120 vs IQ 145 who have achieved some milestone. The base population of the former is 100 times that of the latter!&#8221;</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
